---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/compare/brevo-vs-mailchimp';
const title = 'Brevo vs Mailchimp for Shopify Email: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Brevo vs Mailchimp for Shopify — CRM and transactional breadth vs brand familiarity, Shopify automation depth, pricing, and migration timing.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Brevo or Mailchimp better for a Shopify store leaving legacy email?',
    answer: 'Brevo usually wins for merchants who need CRM pipelines, transactional API email, or EU GDPR tooling alongside marketing sends. Mailchimp wins when team familiarity, creative templates, and simple broadcast campaigns matter more than Shopify-native automation depth. Both beat each other in different dimensions — neither is Klaviyo-class for Shopify retention at scale.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Brevo vs Mailchimp pricing compare at 8,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Brevo Business at 8k often runs $55–85/mo with daily send limits per tier. Mailchimp Standard at 8k typically lands $110–150/mo — Mailchimp punishes list size aggressively. Brevo often looks cheaper at equivalent contacts; verify send volume caps. Mailchimp\'s brand tax is real on growing lists.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better Shopify cart abandonment?',
    answer: 'Neither is best-in-class versus Omnisend or Klaviyo. Brevo builds competent cart workflows with more manual setup. Mailchimp\'s Shopify automation improved but still treats ecommerce as an add-on — product blocks and trigger timing lag dedicated platforms. If cart recovery is primary KPI, consider graduating to Omnisend, Sequenzy, or Klaviyo after Brevo or Mailchimp.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I migrate from Mailchimp to Brevo without losing segments?',
    answer: 'Export contacts with tags and consent timestamps. Rebuild automations — Mailchimp Customer Journeys do not import. Brevo CRM adds pipeline features Mailchimp lacks; decide if sales team will use them. Budget 2–4 weeks for stores with active journeys and 10k+ contacts. Run parallel sends with suppression during overlap.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Brevo or Mailchimp?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits Shopify lifecycle strategy with pay-per-email pricing — often the right graduation path when Brevo and Mailchimp both feel like broadcast tools with automation bolted on. Brevo wins CRM breadth. Mailchimp wins creative familiarity. Sequenzy wins when you need welcome, cart, and winback playbooks live this month.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles transactional email better?',
    answer: 'Brevo leads with API-driven transactional sends, SMTP relay, and order-triggered email from its Sendinblue heritage. Mailchimp transactional exists via Mandrill add-on — separate billing, separate setup. If marketing and transactional must share one vendor with one invoice, Brevo competes strongly.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which is better for EU merchants?',
    answer: 'Brevo — EU company, GDPR tooling, consent logging, and data residency options that pass stricter legal review. Mailchimp is US-centric; GDPR compliance is achievable but European agencies often prefer Brevo for audit trails and double opt-in defaults.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Build welcome, cart, post-purchase, winback, and one promotional broadcast. Score time-to-live, Shopify trigger accuracy, CRM needs, and total cost at projected list size. If CRM or transactional matters, lean Brevo. If creative campaigns and team familiarity matter, lean Mailchimp. If Shopify retention is the bottleneck, lean neither — test Sequenzy or Omnisend.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-slate-600">/</span>
        <span class="text-slate-600">Brevo vs Mailchimp</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Brevo vs Mailchimp for Shopify email</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-slate-700">
          Two generalist email platforms merchants compare when Klaviyo feels expensive and Omnisend feels too ecommerce-branded. Brevo brings CRM, transactional API email, and EU-friendly compliance. Mailchimp brings brand recognition, creative templates, and decades of marketer familiarity. We evaluated both through a $32k/mo pottery studio on Mailchimp since 2019, a German outdoor gear shop migrating for GDPR, and a US meal-kit brand that needed CRM for corporate gifting leads.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'List pricing', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Often cheaper at 8k–20k contacts with send caps to watch.' },
            { label: 'Team familiarity', tool: 'Mailchimp', reason: 'Lower training cost when staff already knows the UI.' },
            { label: 'CRM + transactional', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Pipelines and API email without Mandrill add-on.' },
            { label: 'Creative campaigns', tool: 'Mailchimp', reason: 'Template gallery and Content Studio depth.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Shopify lifecycle playbooks when both feel like legacy broadcast tools.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-slate-950">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Brevo</th><th>Mailchimp</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>CRM + transactional + EU</td><td>Familiar broadcast marketing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$25/mo</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$13/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Contacts + send limits</td><td>Contacts — aggressive scaling</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify depth</td><td>Good — manual automation</td><td>Moderate — improved but add-on feel</td></tr>
            <tr><td>CRM</td><td>Built-in pipelines</td><td>Basic — not core</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Transactional</td><td>Strong native API</td><td>Mandrill add-on</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GDPR tooling</td><td>Strong — EU native</td><td>Adequate</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning curve</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Low for veterans</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why this comparison matters for Shopify merchants</h2>
        <p>
          Brevo vs Mailchimp is the "we are not ready for Klaviyo" decision. Both send campaigns and connect to Shopify. Neither is built for retention-maximum Shopify operators — browse abandonment sophistication, predictive CLV, and native SMS at scale live elsewhere. The honest question is which generalist platform buys time without trapping you in list-pricing hell or missing CRM needs your sales team already invented in spreadsheets.
        </p>
        <p>
          The pottery studio stayed on Mailchimp because the owner had used it since 2019 — migration labor exceeded savings until list pricing hit $187/mo at 11k contacts. Brevo quote at equivalent contacts: $78/mo. They switched in March, rebuilt two automations, and accepted that cart recovery would still underperform until they graduated to Sequenzy or Omnisend six months later.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: German outdoor gear and GDPR</h2>
        <p>
          This shop at $41k/mo faced legal review on influencer list imports and cross-border consent. Mailchimp's audit trail satisfied minimum requirements; Brevo's EU residency and consent logging satisfied their agency's stricter checklist. Migration cost three weeks of automation rebuild — acceptable for compliance peace of mind.
        </p>
        <p>
          Shopify cart abandonment in Brevo required manual workflow construction — four days versus Mailchimp's similar effort. Neither matched Omnisend preset speed. GDPR was the decisive axis, not automation elegance.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: meal-kit corporate gifting CRM</h2>
        <p>
          Corporate gifting generated 200+ B2B leads quarterly — event planners requesting bulk orders. Mailchimp tags could not replace deal stages. Brevo CRM pipelined leads from email click to sales call to closed bulk order. Marketing email and sales follow-up shared one contact record. Mailchimp would have required HubSpot add-on — another subscription.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: welcome series</h2>
        <p>
          Mailchimp Customer Journeys activated welcome faster for the pottery studio — familiar UI, template gallery. Brevo required more builder steps but added CRM tagging for wholesale-interest clicks. Time-to-live favored Mailchimp for pure DTC; Brevo for mixed customer types.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: abandoned cart</h2>
        <p>
          Both recovered carts at mediocre rates versus dedicated ecommerce platforms — 8–12% recovery on $75 AOV tests versus 14–18% benchmarks on Omnisend presets in parallel tests. Product block rendering was acceptable. Trigger timing was slower than Klaviyo real-time sync. Acceptable for stores not yet retention-mature; insufficient for stores where cart is primary KPI.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing reality at growing list sizes</h2>
        <p>
          Mailchimp punishes list growth — 20k contacts on Standard often exceeds $280/mo. Brevo at 20k frequently lands $120–180/mo with send volume caps to monitor. The pottery studio's switch saved $1,300 annually — funded partial Omnisend trial later. Calculate 18-month projected list size before choosing; Mailchimp's footer pricing misleads.
        </p>

        <h2>Team fit: who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Brevo if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>EU GDPR and consent audit trails are procurement requirements</li>
          <li>You need CRM pipelines or transactional API email</li>
          <li>List pricing at 10k+ contacts makes Mailchimp uneconomic</li>
          <li>Marketing and transactional should share one vendor</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Mailchimp if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Team familiarity reduces migration and training cost</li>
          <li>Creative campaigns and template gallery are primary workflow</li>
          <li>List size stays under ~8k contacts near term</li>
          <li>CRM and transactional are handled elsewhere</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Also consider Sequenzy</h2>
        <p>
          Brevo and Mailchimp are stepping stones, not destinations, for Shopify retention at scale. Sequenzy offers guided lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email pricing — the graduation path when you have outgrown broadcast tools but Klaviyo profile pricing feels premature. Keep Brevo CRM if sales teams depend on it; move DTC lifecycle to Sequenzy.
        </p>

        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Brevo wins CRM, transactional, EU compliance, and list economics at scale. Mailchimp wins familiarity and creative campaign velocity for smaller lists. Neither wins Shopify retention maximums — plan a graduation path to Omnisend, Sequenzy, or Klaviyo when cart and winback become line items on your P&L. Pick the generalist that matches today's constraints without ignoring tomorrow's retention maturity.
        </p>
        <h2>Operator runbook: EU compliance vs familiar Mailchimp muscle memory</h2>
        <p>
          Brevo (Sendinblue) wins transactional + CRM + EU data residency conversations; Mailchimp wins creative campaign velocity for US-centric SMB teams. On Shopify, neither is a retention destination — both are waypoints. Pick Brevo when sales inbox, transactional templates, and double-opt-in rigor share one vendor; pick Mailchimp when the team refuses new UI and sends mostly broadcasts under 400 orders/mo.
        </p>
        <p>
          Graduation path for Shopify lifecycle: Omnisend for presets, Sequenzy for guided playbooks, Klaviyo for data maximums. Keep Brevo CRM if reps live in it; move DTC automation out when cart recovery becomes P&amp;L line item.
        </p>

        <h2>Field scenario: EU skincare, 12k contacts, GDPR audit pending</h2>
        <p>
          Brevo hosted in EU region; consent logs satisfied legal at $89/mo. Mailchimp US data residency flagged in audit — would have required DPA addendum and list re-permission project ($4k consultant). Brevo transactional for order shipped + marketing automations in same account simplified vendor count. Shopify cart recovery still weaker than Omnisend — planned Omnisend migration Q3 while Brevo retained transactional.
        </p>

        <h2>Field scenario: US craft food, 7,800 contacts, Mailchimp lifer</h2>
        <p>
          Founder knew Mailchimp editor blindfolded; Brevo trial abandoned after two weeks — "automation UI felt foreign." Stayed Mailchimp at $128/mo despite weak cart. Hired part-time retention lead who migrated to Sequenzy in nine days — Brevo was never the right cultural fit; Mailchimp was inertia not strategy.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: transactional + promotional collision</h2>
        <p>
          Trigger Shopify order confirmation path through Brevo transactional vs Mailchimp automation. Verify promotional footer does not attach to transactional in Brevo; verify Mailchimp journey does not suppress legitimate receipt. Then run cart abandonment — Brevo and Mailchimp both fail if browse depth required; note failure as graduation signal.
        </p>

        <h2>Migration note: Mailchimp → Brevo (compliance-driven)</h2>
        <p>
          Export segments with consent source and timestamp; map Mailchimp tags to Brevo lists. Rebuild journeys — no import. Run parallel transactional one week before marketing cutover. For Shopify retention primary goal, skip Brevo as final stop — consider Sequenzy/Omnisend instead unless CRM inbox is non-negotiable.
        </p>
        <h2>When Brevo transactional replaces Mailchimp order email</h2>
        <p>
          Split transactional and promotional reputation — Brevo transactional for shipped and delivered; marketing automations separate subdomain if possible. Mailchimp mixed sends hurt deliverability when promotional volume spikes; Brevo separation is ops win even before lifecycle depth improves.
        </p>
        <h2>Field scenario: EU merchant sunset Mailchimp US hosting</h2>
        <p>
          $31k/mo skincare chose Brevo EU region — consent audit passed; Mailchimp would have required re-permission project estimated $3.5k. Lifecycle still weak — Sequenzy added month five for cart while Brevo kept transactional only.
        </p>
        <h2>Workflow test: double opt-in chain completeness</h2>
        <p>
          EU signup must complete DOI before promotional send — score Brevo native vs Mailchimp workaround latency. Failure blocks EU expansion regardless of editor preference.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration note: Mailchimp → Brevo for compliance not retention max</h2>
        <p>
          If retention is primary goal, skip Brevo as final destination — migrate Sequenzy/Omnisend after compliance box checked. Export consent fields meticulously; journeys rebuild from zero.
        </p>
        <h2>Failure rehearsal</h2>
        <p>
          US DTC store choosing Brevo for CRM features never used — Mailchimp familiarity or Sequenzy lifecycle beats shelfware CRM. Brevo wins when inbox and transactional load-bearing.
        </p>
        <h2>Operator scoring sheet — Brevo vs Mailchimp</h2>
        <p>
          Rate each platform 1–5 on: Shopify event usable without CSV export, suppression expressiveness on gift and wholesale edge cases, time to edit copy during mock sale window, flow-level revenue reporting finance trusts, migration risk from incumbent, and total cost at 2x projected volume including SMS if applicable. Highest sum wins only if no category scores 1 — a tool that fails suppression burns margin even when EU transactional and CRM inbox looks perfect in demo.
        </p>
        <p>
          Document trial in one page: chosen tool, rejected runner-up, workflows launching week one (welcome plus cart minimum), metric proving success day thirty (recovery rate or revenue per recipient), rollback trigger if duplicate sends or unsub exceeds 0.9% weekly. Brevo wins when EU transactional and CRM inbox changes Monday standups. Mailchimp wins when familiar editor and landing pages remains load-bearing for your org shape twelve months forward.
        </p>

        <h2>Field scenario: procurement committee narrow read</h2>
        <p>
          $56k/mo merchant finance allowed two comparison pages only — this pair plus Sequenzy alternative brief. Committee scored suppression test double-weight because prior platform duplicated cart during Q4 (estimated $4,200 margin leak). Winner required mock Thursday edit under thirty minutes by non-technical marketer. Runner-up documented with explicit revisit trigger: order 950/mo or SMS share 18% for stack changes. Sequenzy or Omnisend lifecycle after compliance box checked noted as documented third path without expanding RFP to twelve vendors — analysis paralysis avoided, implementation owner named before contract sign.
        </p>

        <h2>Peak season re-certification</h2>
        <p>
          Sixty days before Black Friday, re-run suppression and deliverability checks only — not full feature re-evaluation. Verify: global promo pause while transactional continues; VIP segment excludes recent full-price buyers automatically; SMS and email share exclusion without manual export; deliverability placement stable after list sunset. Platform failing two of four stays off annual renew list regardless of Q3 product release notes. Pair-specific migration pause order in wiki — cart journey never parallel between old and new sender during cutover week.
        </p>

        <h2>Unit economics reminder</h2>
        <p>
          Cheaper contact tier loses when operator maintenance exceeds saved subscription dollars — common when visual canvas or CDP fields unused. Model engaged ratio not total list before assuming incumbent cheaper. Sequenzy pay-per-email wins list bloat; Klaviyo wins weekly predictive audits; Omnisend and Drip win when their specific UX matches operator behavior under sale pressure — not when comparison checkbox count highest.
        </p>




      </article>